"variants":[{"name":"Buttler","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Butler  .","German: occupational name for a village tavern owner, from French <i>bouteillier</i> ‘butler’.","Americanized form of German <b>Buttlar</b>: habitational name from a place so named in Thuringia."]},{"name":"Bouthillier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Jacques, Normand, Philippe, Yves.","French: variant of   Bouteiller  . This name is sometimes Americanized as   Butler  . Compare   Boutilier  ."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":65,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margery Butler was born before 1390, her father, Andreus Butler, was 11386 and her mother, Catherine Carbonel, was 11386. She had at least 2 sons with William Crane."},"et":{"Bef 1390–":"enne 1390–Surnud","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1390–1455":"1390–1455","1398–Male":"1398–Surnud","1410–1500":"1410–1500","1370–1429":"1370–1429","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1500":"1500","Bef 1410":"enne 1410","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1398":"1398","1373":"1373","1370":"1370","Bef 1390":"enne 1390","1429":"1429","1390":"1390","Great Waldingfield, Suffolk, England":"Great Waldin